context: Yale's residential college system was established in <a0_0><b5_0>1933<b5_0/><a0_0/> by <a1_0><b6_0>Edward S. Harkness<b6_0/><a1_0/>, who admired the social intimacy of Oxford and Cambridge and donated significant funds to found similar colleges at Yale and Harvard. Though Yale's colleges resemble their English precursors organizationally and architecturally, they are dependent entities of Yale College and have limited autonomy. <a2_0><b7_0>The colleges are led by a master and an academic dean<b7_0/><a2_0/>, who reside in the college, and university faculty and affiliates comprise each college's fellowship. Colleges offer their own seminars, social events, and speaking engagements known as "Master's Teas," but <a3_0><b8_0>do not contain programs of study or academic departments<b8_0/><a3_0/>. Instead, all undergraduate courses are taught by the <a4_0><b9_0>Faculty of Arts and Sciences<b9_0/><a4_0/> and are open to members of any college.
